<div id="review_497510659" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/497510659" />
    <a title="Marc" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2876105-marc"><img alt="Marc" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1569160429p2/2876105.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/497510659?book_show_action=true">Jan 06, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Marc" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Marc" href="/user/show/2876105-marc">Marc</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2876105-marc?shelf=french-literature">french-literature</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2876105-marc?shelf=18th-century">18th-century</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer497510659" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6813377445338580881">This is one of the most intruiging early novels (end of the 18th C.). The construction of the story is utterly sublime, as an epistolary novel with letters going back and forth between the Marquise de Merteuil and the Vicomte de Valmont (both amoral, narcistic personalities), full of mirror effects and hidden parallels.<br/><br/>The originality of this work is that this is one of the first novels in history in which words and language are used in a very perverse way (it set the mark for thousands of other</span>
  <span id="freeText6813377445338580881" style="display:none">This is one of the most intruiging early novels (end of the 18th C.). The construction of the story is utterly sublime, as an epistolary novel with letters going back and forth between the Marquise de Merteuil and the Vicomte de Valmont (both amoral, narcistic personalities), full of mirror effects and hidden parallels.<br /><br />The originality of this work is that this is one of the first novels in history in which words and language are used in a very perverse way (it set the mark for thousands of others), inviting the reader to permanently search for the hidden meaning behind what is written. Instead of what most people think, the real focus of the story is not on seduction, but on power. And not the character of the libertarist count Valmont is new in literature, but that of the vilain marquise de Merteuil, making the novel - again in very perverse way - a forerunner in emancipated literature. I read this in the original French version, which of course adds to the exquisiteness of the novel.<br /><br />Addendum: one of the best female Dutch authors of the 20th Century, Hella S. Haasse, has written a beautiful sequel on this novel, <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/1248747.Een_gevaarlijke_verhouding_of_Daal_en_Bergse_brieven" title="Een gevaarlijke verhouding of Daal-en-Bergse brieven by Hella S. Haasse" rel="nofollow noopener">Een gevaarlijke verhouding of Daal-en-Bergse brieven</a>. She uses the perspective of the marquise de Merteuil, living her last days in The Hague, and musing on the female condition. Very recommended, although unfortunately it has only been translated in French, not in English.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6813377445338580881" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


